node.text:
Check out where we take the trash recovered by our captains and crews in Guatemala! 

Over the last couple weeks, we’ve explored the causes of plastic pollution in Guatemala and shared our strategy for addressing the ocean plastic crisis in this region. Now, we’re taking you behind the scenes of our main operational base in Puerto Barrios, which is the first stop for the trash our crews recover from the ocean.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Visit the link in our bio to learn more about where we take our recovered trash in Guatemala! 🇬🇹

Are you obsessed with the clean ocean movement? Do you brag about our mission to all your friends? Are you taking steps to reduce your plastic footprint? Do you encourage others to reduce theirs? ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
If you answered “Yes!” this is your chance to become a 4ocean Brand Ambassador and earn cash doing what you already do! ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
We're beyond stoked to launch this brand new program that gives YOU the opportunity to grow the clean ocean movement, and earn awesome rewards while doing so. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Click the link in our bio to learn more about the 4ocean Brand Ambassador Program and submit your application 📲⁠⁠
⁠⁠
#4ocean #brandambassador #brand #oceanplastic #plasticpollution #breakfreefromplastic #saveourseas

#breakfreefromplastic #plasticpollution #4ocean #oceanplastic

node.text:
We know that cleaning the ocean and empowering individuals to use alternative products is not enough to stop plastic pollution. We must take bold steps to advocate for policy change that will hold brands, manufacturers, and the plastics industry accountable for their significant contributions to the ocean plastic crisis.

We are proud to support the Break Free From Plastic Pollution Act and are calling on every member of the clean ocean movement to join us. The Break Free From Plastic Pollution Act is a comprehensive piece of federal legislation in the U.S. that provides a comprehensive approach to reducing plastic pollution. 
To find out how you can get involved, visit 4ocean.com/breakfree today!

Having ongoing support from people in all industries is imperative to the success of the clean ocean movement. Thank you so much to every single person and group who has shared our story with their followers, friends and families over the years.

We appreciate each and every one of you and look forward to fighting for a cleaner ocean with you for many years to come. Onward!

node.text:
We’re partnering with Safe Harbor for cleaner marinas across the country.

Ever since we introduced the 4ocean Harbor Skimmer, it’s been our 
dream to see it used in harbors and marinas around the world. 
Well, today, we’re stoked to announce that our dream is coming true!

Safe Harbor Marinas, the world’s largest owner and operator of marinas, has agreed to install 4ocean Harbor Skimmers in several of their locations across the country.

Our partnership will begin with a pilot program in Florida before ultimately expanding nationwide — a deployment that would likely involve more than 97 locations.

This is HUGE news and would not be possible without the support of our clean ocean movement and people like you! Every time you purchase a 4ocean product, it helps fund the removal of marine debris from the ocean and supports our efforts to develop and install clean ocean technologies around the world.

Project Guatemala Update: You’ve been following us along as we’ve introduced the next challenge our 4ocean Cleanup Crews will face. Now we want to take you on tour of our HQ in Guatemala where we’ll be setting up operations that will allow us to clean the ocean and coastlines in Central America. 
Stay tuned for the next update. 
#4ocean #WeAre4ocean #ProjectGuatemala

Head over to the link in our bio to pull a pound today.

node.text:
We're stoked to be partnering with our friends at @OneOceanDiving this month!

Together, we'll help raise awareness about the importance of protecting hammerhead sharks and all of the apex predators that keep our oceans healthy and balanced 🌊 

Our donation will be used to help fund crucial research, education, and protection initiatives that advance shark conservation globally. With shark populations dwindling around the world, it’s crucial that we save as many as possible.

Visit the link in our bio to learn more about One Ocean Diving and to secure your limited edition Hammerhead Shark Bracelet!

ODD FINDS: Single-use plastic isn't the only thing our crews find! Check out some of these strange finds we recently came across.
⁠⁠
From couches and boxing gloves, to cell phones, fans, and fake hands .. our crews find it all!⁠⁠
⁠⁠
We're always wondering how odd items like these make their way to the ocean, rivers, and coastlines.⁠ But regardless of how they got there, they won't be staying there thanks to you and all the pounds you pull.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Which of these items do you think is the strangest? Tell us below!⁠⁠

node.text:
Swipe to see Team Haiti beautify this beach!

This coastline in St. Marc was engulfed with plastic debris. After a few hours, our cleanup crews were able to collect over 2,000 pounds of trash and restore the natural beauty of this beach. That puts Team Haiti at 884,459 total pounds of trash recovered so far this year!

Incredible differences like this one are only possible because of the pounds pulled by the clean ocean movement.

Together, we can restore gorgeous beaches like this one, around the world 🌍

node.text:
Abandoned fishing gear is wreaking havoc on the ocean!

10% of all marine debris accounts for lost and abandoned fishing gear like nets, traps, pots, ropes, and buoys.. Once lost, fishing gear becomes a significant entanglement risk that can cause serious harm to marine life. 

Our cleanup crews are finding thousands of pounds of abandoned fishing gear weekly. In fact, fishing gear accounts for up to 15% of the trash recovered by our crews in Bali each week. As part of our global ocean cleanup mission, we are committed to removing these harmful nets from the environment.

To learn more about abandoned fishing gear and to read our Analysis of the Global Fishing Industry, visit the link in our bio 🐟

node.text:
Meet our Partner of the Month — One Ocean Diving!

As we continue to learn more about the Hawai'ian Islands and the effects of plastic pollution, we are working with local partners to support cleanup and community outreach initiatives that have existed on the islands. So this month, we’re donating $1 to our friends at @OneOceanDiving for every Hammerhead Shark Bracelet sold! 

One Ocean Diving, Research & Conservation is a Hawai'i-based organization that funds crucial marine research and conservation initiatives while raising awareness about the importance of protecting sharks and other marine life. 

Together, we'll help fund crucial research, education, and protection initiatives that advance shark conservation globally 🦈 🌎 

Visit the link in our bio to learn more about One Ocean Diving, the projects our donation will support, and to secure your limited edition Hammerhead Shark Bracelet!

An estimated 80% of ocean plastic pollution comes from land-based sources as “mismanaged waste” 

That’s the case here on the coastline of Guatemala. Heavy inland rains are causing trash from country’s landfill to pour into the Motagua River. The river pushes the trash downstream and into the ocean, where currents push it back onto Guatemala’s shore. 

Help us curb the ocean plastic crisis in Guatemala by pulling a pound at 4ocean.com today!

NEW: Hammerhead Shark Bracelets!

We’re introducing our limited edition Hammerhead Shark Bracelets in partnership with One Ocean Diving, Research & Conservation to raise awareness about the dual threats of plastic pollution and overfishing that are causing hammerheads to disappear from our oceans. 

Hammerhead sharks are apex predators usually found in the coastal waters of warmer seas. The combined threats of overfishing and entanglement in marine debris have caused some populations to decline by as much as 80%. Right now, 6 of 9 hammerhead species are threatened with extinction, which is why they’re our cause of the month for August 2021. 

Visit the link in our bio to learn more about our partnership with @OneOceanDiving and to get your limited edition Hammerhead Shark Bracelets!

It's been over a year of finding disposable face masks littering the ocean, rivers, and coastlines around the world!

As we're over a year into this pandemic, our cleanup crews are still finding hundreds of face masks in the environment every single week.

Studies show that roughly 129 BILLION single-use face masks are being used every single month. When these masks aren't properly disposed of, they make their way into the environment.

This cannot be the new normal. 

Please consider using a reusable face mask. If you can't, please ensure you're properly disposing of your single-use masks so that they don't end up as pollution where they can cause serious harm to wildlife.

ICYMI: We recently introduced our new BeBot, a beach cleaning robot!

Our crew has received a few questions from the clean ocean movement about this new groundbreaking clean ocean technology, so we thought we'd share some FAQs and our answers below ⬇️ 

1. Will this machine cause harm to wildlife in the sand, such as crabs and turtle nests?
➡️ The BeBot was strategically designed to clean the top 10cm of a beach in order to avoid any marine life. It's controlled by our team, so we can avoid any environmentally sensitive areas or hazards, such as nests. In addition, it's exceptionally lightweight for a sifting vehicle, and  is able to operate while applying exceptionally low pressure on the sand. Its unique tracks allow the BeBot to equally distribute the pressure applied on the sand with a sinking level that is 3 to 5 times lower than a traditional vehicle of the same weight. Any living things smaller than the sifter mesh size will simply fall back into the sand without harm. If any critters do make their way through the sifter and into the collection bin, they can be easily removed by hand and safely returned to the environment by our crew member.

2. How can I acquire one of these machines for my local beach?
➡️ Visit the link in our bio, select 'Bebot - The Beach Cleaning Robot', fill out the 'Contact us' form on that webpage, then one of our crew members will get in touch with you shortly.

3. What is this machine made of?
➡️ The BeBot is designed using many different materials to sustain coastal conditions, including metal, rubber, plastic and glass.

To learn more about the BeBot, which was designed by robotic engineers and deployed by @Poralu_Marine, visit the link in our bio!

Meet the BeBot, a beach cleaning robot!

We’re stoked to introduce the BeBot, a groundbreaking piece of clean ocean technology engineered by robotic experts and deployed by @Poralu_Marine 🌊

The BeBot, short for beach cleaning robot, is an eco-friendly device that’s specifically designed to clean and restore our coastlines without harming the environment.

The 100% electric BeBot runs on battery and solar power, therefore it releases zero harmful emissions. It's designed to sift sand up to 10cm deep to recover trash that can be as small as 1cm Over the course of an hour, our BeBot can clean up to 3,000 meters, or roughly the size of 7 basketball courts!

Over the next few weeks, 4ocean will be testing the BeBot on beaches near our headquarters in South Florida. Once testing is complete, we’ll deploy an additional unit in Hawai'i to support our local partners and existing cleanup initiatives on the island of Oahu.

Visit the link in our bio to learn more about this groundbreaking clean ocean technology, and remember, this is what you make possible every time you pull a pound!
